[normal]Let us just think this through for a minute. If the Government introduced into 
[normal]Parliament
[normal] a Bill that infringed a fundamental right, whereas in the United States and in France these constitutional controls are extra-
[normal]parliament
[normal]ary—whether it be the 
[normal]Conseil
[normal] 
[normal]Constitutionnel
[normal] in France or the US Supreme Court in America—in Britain the controls are intra-
[normal]parliament
[normal]ary. I think Lord Lester explained this in his evidence here. Under section 19 the Minister has to declare that the Bill is incompatible with the Human Rights Act. There is the Joint Parliamentary Committee on Human Rights. There is the Lords Constitution 
[normal]Committee
[normal]. They would all be looking at this Bill and saying, “We have a problem, what is the Government going to do about it?” This is also a defence of 
[normal]parliament
[normal]ary sovereignty rather than executive dominance because the Government still has to work through 
[normal]Parliament
[normal] in order to get legislation passed. Can the Government, if it really wants to, get the Bill through? Yes, we know that it can, but there is also an orderly 
[normal]parliament
[normal]ary process
[normal]Richard Gordon[bold]: Can I just expand on that? What Jo is saying is in a different way exactly what I have tried to say, which is that 
[normal]Parliament
[normal] can do anything it wants provided it can practically achieve it. So it can’t remove Canadian independence but it could certainly withdraw from the 
[normal]European
[normal] Convention, and that is what may happen if one party gets in next time. It would be a manifesto commitment. But I am afraid the problem is that it will be perceived by a large section of the organs of state as going too far, I think, in the sense that there is very strong support for the progress we have made since enacting the Human Rights Act. 
[normal]To give you a graphic example, when I went to 
[normal]Singapore
[normal] a year ago I looked at their constitution and I also looked at the cases that have been brought before their courts and talked to the Attorney General’s chambers. Oddly enough when I got back from 
[normal]Singapore
[normal] I was briefed by the leader of the Opposition and I said to him that he had a strong case that he was bound to lose. He said, “How can that be?” and I said, “Because there has never been a successful constitutional challenge in 
[normal]Singapore
[normal]. Statistically you have no hope whatever”. That is a different legal culture, but the point is that all the rules in Singaporean administrative law, you could go back in this country 30, 40 years and they were our rules: ultra 
[normal]vires
[normal], the dominant principle, and so on. 
[normal]I think shifting from the convention would send a huge political signal to the Council of Europe members; it would endanger our relationship with the EU and it would cause a constitutional destabilisation. But the answer to your question is that 
[normal]Parliament
[normal] holds the trump card. There is no doubt about that. My point is that holding the trump card in a constitution such as we have is not enough. It is the sensible application of a consensual set of rules that will produce stable government.
[normal]Professor [bold]Masterman[bold]: All I can add to that is that it is perhaps one of the unfortunate consequences of 
[normal]parliament
[normal]ary sovereignty that the idea of unlimited legal power, and maybe unquestionable legal power, has been allowed to survive for this long. The difficulty of course is that it does not give rise to anything approaching a meaningful dialogue. It simply results in one party to the dispute saying, “I have an unquestionable legal right to do this”, which is no kind of working towards a consensus on anything.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q146 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Durkan[bold]:[bold] I suppose it partly takes us back to the question of looking at issues at a pre-enactment stage. There is the option 
[normal]obviously
[normal] in pre-enactment review of that being done on the basis of referral, perhaps by 
[normal]Parliament
[normal] as a result of pre-legislative scrutiny. If there is that referral the issue then is does whoever is giving it judicial consideration simply determine whether something is compatible with whatever constitutional principles or provisions are in question, or do we leave it that 
[normal]there is no such review or reference in advance but in the event of a codified constitution the judiciary can subsequently strike down legislation?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Richard Gordon[bold]: I originally was a great advocate of referral. I am now much less of an advocate. I am acting at the moment for the National Assembly for 
[normal]Wales
[normal] and the Counsel General is referring a Bill at the moment. 
[normal]I think it is quite dangerous because it leads the judiciary in the abstract to pronounce on the legality of a Bill that has not yet come into law and it could affect the position later. They might declare a Bill to be lawful and you might get a challenge later. Later events come into play and it is quite difficult then for the judges to pronounce it unlawful. I think there are problems with references. I also happen to think there are problems with simply striking down legislation and I do not think it is solved remedially by prospective declarations, which have caused all sorts of problems in 
[normal]Hong Kong
[normal], for example.
[normal]My current thinking, having started off as a huge advocate of a classic codified 
[normal]constitution
[normal], is to say it should all be done incrementally. I would love to see a codified 
[normal]constitution
[normal]. It will happen at some stage, maybe 100 years down the line, but you have to do these things incrementally. I do not think you can do more at the moment—but I think you should go this far—than to draft a framework that sets out the essential concepts and rules that the judiciary have a hand in formulating. That is how I think the thing should happen but that is only a personal view.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q147 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Durkan[bold]:[bold] Do we not find ourselves between pre-enactment review and post-enactment strike-down, that when you think of either you prefer the other? Is there a way in which we can have a sensible option of both?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Richard Gordon[bold]: You have it at the moment. You have the very ingenious solution of the declaration of incompatibility. It does not affect an Act of 
[normal]Parliament
[normal]. It goes on, it is valid, but it sends a warning shot and in all cases but one—
[normal]Mark [bold]Durkan[bold]:[bold] Even with a codified 
[normal]constitution
[normal] we can keep that element?
[normal]Richard Gordon[bold]: You can keep that and in only one case, I think, has the Government not made a remedial order and that was because it was academic. I cannot remember the case now, but in every case the Government has ultimately acted.
[normal]Professor [bold]Masterman[bold]: I think the declaration of incompatibility—or unconstitutionality as you might call it in the event of a written 
[normal]constitution
[normal]—is an excellent proposal and something that deserves further thought. It is the remedy that effectively straddles the ideas of the rule of law and the ideas relating to 
[normal]parliament
[normal]ary 
[normal]sovereignty
[normal] because it respects the democratic will of the legislature by not affecting the validity of the legislation—or at least not explicitly doing so—yet allows the courts to vindicate the rule of law by saying that there is an issue here of compatibility with the 
[normal]constitution
[normal] or the convention rights or whatever objective standard you are hoping to balance legislation against. So it is the mechanism that arguably in theory allows for this dialogue, allows for 
[normal]a collaboration
[normal] between the branches of government, that does not necessarily result in one always having a trump card to play.
[normal]Dr [bold]Murkens[bold]: This dialogue is not just a matter of institutional comity; it is a matter of necessity because of the breadth of law. If we think about this, when 
[normal]Parliament
[normal] legislates, it legislates for the nation. 
[normal]Parliament
[normal] is the forum of the nation. It cannot ever anticipate all the individual repercussions that will emerge somewhere down the line. That is for the courts to solve. The courts are there to protect individual justice. That bias is ingrained in the judicial system. When the courts say that we have an issue here with individual justice that has emerged further down the line and 
[normal]that therefore shines a negative light on the integrity of the statute as a whole, the judges have to have some mechanism in which to say a 
[normal]constitution
[normal]al issue has arisen. Right now—but only since 2000—that mechanism is built into the Human Rights Act. But as we say, and others have pointed out as well, we could create a common-law declaration of unconstitutionality that would preserve 
[normal]parliament
[normal]ary 
[normal]sovereignty
[normal] but would also allow the judges to say an issue has emerged after the fact, and this is how we highlight it.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q148 [bold]&#xa0; 
